
POCs are where Claude Code shines. What took weeks now takes hours. [Andrej Karpathy coined the term "vibe coding" in February 2025](https://simonwillison.net/2025/Feb/6/andrej-karpathy/) to describe this: describe what you want in natural language, Claude generates code, you iterate conversationally until it works. The term became [Collins Dictionary's Word of the Year 2025](https://www.collinsdictionary.com/woty).

For production code, follow the disciplined approach covered throughout this guide. But for POCs? Different rules apply.

## When Vibe Coding Works

**Meeting demos**: Someone asks "what if we added feature X?" Don't wait for design mockups. Open Claude Code and build a working prototype during the meeting. Stakeholders respond better to interactive demos than slide decks.

**Idea validation**: Before investing engineering resources, prove the concept works. A POC that fails early is a success. It saved you from a costly mistake.

**Internal tools**: Need a quick dashboard, data transformer, or admin interface? These don't require production polish. Build them in a lunch break.

**Customer discovery**: Build clickable demos for user interviews. Real feedback on real interactions beats hypothetical discussions every time.

As [Karpathy described it](https://simonwillison.net/2025/Feb/6/andrej-karpathy/): "I just see stuff, say stuff, run stuff, and copy paste stuff, and it mostly works." That's the vibe.

## POC vs Prototype vs MVP

Understanding what you're building changes how you build it:

| Type | Purpose | Audience | Polish Level |
|------|---------|----------|--------------|
| **POC** | Prove technical feasibility | Internal team | Rough, just needs to work |
| **Prototype** | Validate UX and design | Stakeholders, users | Visual, should feel real |
| **MVP** | Test market demand | Real customers | Functional, minimum shippable |

Claude Code is ideal for POCs and prototypes. For MVPs heading to production, add the guardrails from other sections of this guide.

